fields.descriptive_line: Album of designs by W. Harry Rogers (1825-1873) from the W.H.Rogers Archive.
fields.physical_description:
[album of designs] Album of designs for book, magazine and periodical covers, dedication pages, wrapping paper for notepaper, illustrations for the catalogues of the Great Exhibitions and international exhibitions, designs for engraved glass decanters.  The designs, many of which are in pencil, are stuck into the pages of the album.  The album has buckram covers in a watered design with the words 'SCRAP BOOK' stamped and gilded onto the front cover.
[design in an album] Sketch in pencil, pen and ink and wash for a dedication page to Robert Vernon depicting an oval, inscribed reserve within an elaborate border of scrolling acanthus topped by a coat of arms.
[design from an album] Pencil sketch of a reserve, inscribed in pen and ink, surrounded by a border of trophies for Chemistry, Music etc. amidst acanthus and surmounted by the initials 'N' for the Emperor Napoleon and 'E' for the Empress Eugenie.
[design from an album] Design for the word 'GARDEN' spelt backwards on a long, narrow strip of paper.
[design from an album] Design, in pencil, for the book cover for 'Effie's Friends' spelt backwards.
[design from an album] Design inscribed with the title 'Great Battles of the British Army' on a cartouche on a small, square piece of paper.
[design from an album] Design for wrapping paper with an ornamental border arranged vertically on a rectangular sheet of paper.
[design] Design for the spine of a bookcover on a thin, vertical strip of paper. The title and author's name are enclosed in a printed strapwork border over pencil ornament.
[design from an album] Perspective drawing of a presentation box in pencil.
[design from an album] Design for the cover of a magazine with the title enclosed by ornament.
[design] Design,on an irregularly shaped piece of paper, depicting the title with a barrel on top and a rocket shooting up diagonally from the lower right side.
[design from an album] Design for wrapping paper for a packet depicting inscription surrounded by ornament on brown tracing paper.
[design from an album] Designs for vignettes on a half finished letter.
[design] Three designs for vignettes, arranged horizontally one above the other, on a roughly square piece of cream-coloured wove paper.
[design from an album] Rough, unfinished sketch depicting a central, inscribed reserve with parts of an ornmental border on a large sheet of paper which fills the album page.
[design] Designs for a bookcover and spine on two pieces of paper laid side to side and covering the album page.  The interior designs are diapered and the bookcover has an ornamental border.
[design from an album] Design depicting a beehive, typography and ornament on a rectangular sheet of greyish paper.
[design from an album] Narrow, vertical design for the spine of a book on cream-coloured paper.
[design from an album] Design for an engraved glass jug cut to the shape of the jug and decorated with ornament.  The design is on two sheets of paper which are joined down the middle.
[design from an album] Design for bookcover with an ornamental border sent for approval within a letter.  The design is loose within the cover of the album.
[design from an album] Full page design, pen and ink, with title on strapwork surrounded by ornament.  The design is cut on the right side.
[Manuscript from an album] Letter on a small, sheet of cream-coloured paper, folded into two, and  written in pen and brown ink.  The sheet is creased in two places.  There is a diagram of a triangle surrounded by rays representing 'glory' on the bottom front.  The letter continues inside the sheet  with a similar diagram at the top.
[design from an album] Trade card for Mr Edmund Evans printed in gold letters on a black ground surrounded by  a white border.
[design] Design, in pencil, depicting an inscribed reserve surrounded by an elaborate, scrolling acanthus border surmounted by the imperial crown of Napoleon III.
[design] Design, in pencil, for the title page of a publication for the International Exhibition of 1851 depicting a crowned beehive, within a central circle, flanked by flags within circles.
[design] Design for a book title showing trophies in heart shapes within an ornamental border.
[design] Design for a bookcover with an inner rectangular border of ornament with circles formed by a compass at each corner.  The border frames the inscribed title of the book.
[design from an album] Two narrow, vertical designson two pieces of greyish paper.
[design from an album] Design for a magazine cover depicting a reserve surmounted by an inkwell and surrounded by acanthus.  The design is drawn on the back of an addressed, blank and opened out letter which fills the album page.
[design from an album] Design, in pencil, for a bookcover which covers the whole of the end board of the album.  There is a frame of ornament on all four sides of the bookcover in the centre of which is a fleur-de-lys.
[design from an album] Ornamental typography, printed in black ink, on a small, rectangular sheet of cream-coloured paper.
[print from an album] The arms of Moubray of Cockairny showing a man in contemporary and a woman in classical dress on either side of a shield emblazoned with a lion rampant. Part of the crest is crossed out in pen and brown ink and the outline of the shield has been altered in pencil  .
[Manuscript from an album] Manuscript, in pen & brown ink, copying the text concerning the grant of arms to John Winchcombe on a long, rectangular sheet of paper.  Above the manuscript is a smaller, attached sheet on which are depicted the coat of arms on the front and a drawing of a panel with the monogram of Jack of Tewbury on the back.  The latter drawing extends over the joint between the two sheets of paper.
[design from an album] Design for the letter 'N' in an ornamental border on a small piece of paper which is folded down one side and on which is a lion passant on the back of which is the head of an antelope.
[design from an album] A very small piece of paper, creased when once folded into four, with an ornamental border down one side and the monogram 'PC' on the other side.
[design] Design, in pencil, of the letter 'O' over which is ornament on a tiny fragment of paper which is folded down one side.
[design from an album] Small piece of paper on which is an ornamental border down one side of a vertical crease.
[design from an album] Design, in pencil, for the spine of Shakespeare's 'Works' depicting typography, the volume number within a circle and a shield surrounded by strapwork on a narrow rectangular sheet of cream-coloured paper.
[design] Design for a bookcover with the title in a circular frame in the centre with asymmetrical foliage on either side.
[design from an album] Part of a design, in pencil, for bookcover.
[design from an album] Design for the bookcover of an edition of the 'Holy Bible' in pencil.
[design from an album] Design for headed writing paper for the Builder Office.
[design] A small girl in a yellow dress catching a capital letter 'S' on an irregularly shaped piece of paper.
[design] Small boy, painted in blue and yellow, stepping out to catch a figure of eight.
[design] Drawing of a slice of bread, impaled by a knife, on a plate on a small, squarish piece of paper.
[design] Drawing of a hare standing on its hind legs in the middle of undergrowth.
[design from an album] Design, in pencil, for typescript ornamented with a hanging lantern and a barrel.
[design from an album] Design, in pencil, for the spine of a book depicting a sword above a shield emblazoned with lions rampant.
[design from an album] Horizontal design, in pencil, showing two sheilds with lions rampant.
[design from an album] Horizontal design showing two shields on either side of a central fleur-de-lys.
[design from an album] Horizontal design, in pen and ink and pencil, depicting a line of three ornamental circles with a shield on either end.
[design from an album] Horizontal design, in pencil and pen and ink, depicting two upright shields, one with a lion rampant.
[design from an album] Vertical design, in pencil, with a central quatrefoil and ornamental leaves.
[design from an album] Vertical design, in pencil, depicting a line of squares, each with an internal a cross.
[design from an album] Horizontal design, in pencil, depicting two shields on either side of central fleurs-de-lys.
[design from an album] Horizontal design with a central circle containing a horse and ornament at either end of the narrow piece of paper.
[design from an album] Horizontal design, in pencil, depicting scrolling acanthus.
[design from an album] Horizontal design, in pencil, depicting a central Tudor rose flanked by a fleur-de-lys at either end of the narrow sheet of paper.

fields.history_note:
[album of designs] Historical significance: These designs are part of the W.Harry Rogers Archive and to quote the information on the archive provided by 'RW' on 6 February 1998 on the registered file 1997/1476:-
'It is extraordinarily rare to have this kind of documentation at this level of production for the middle decades of the 19th century.  The fact the (sic) the state of the designs ranges from rough sketches to finished drawings and proofs allows the pieces to document the design process very closely.'
[design from an album] There is a version of this design in pen and ink and pencil, lacking the inscription, but retaining the initials 'N' 'E' in another album of designs in theWH Rogers Archive.  The museum number is E.693.12-1998
[design from an album] This design was used for the actual spine of the 1869 edition of the book.  See the proof of the spine E.693.174-1998.
[design from an album] Perspective drawing to be converted into a wood-engraving for the illustrated catalogues of the international exhibitions.
[design] Dr Jenny Brown thinks that this is the design for the title page to an individual story in a book containing a selection of stories entitled 'The Busch' 'Bushel of Merrythoughts'
[design from an album] There is an edition of 'Fairy Realm' by Thomas Hood the younger which is illustrated by Gustave Dore in the British Library 1871.d.23.  The bookcover for this edition is not the same as this desin.
[Manuscript from an album] This letter is from  Hyde Pullen, the commissioner of the design, to Wyman, the engraver.  It is about cutting a block for printing a design for a certificate by WH Rogers.  The commissioner of the design, Pullen, suggests that the artist, WH Rogers, alter the design to be cut on the block.  Wyman sent the printing block to the client, Pullen, who returned with this covering letter.  Pullen shows how he would like the design to be altered by drawing two designs in the letter.  He states:

'All will do very nicely, except the rays of "Glory" - which should emanate from the triangle, but without the dark circle around - thus - not like the copy, thus: this can be rectified no doubt: - & if the Lions in the flag could be cut a little nearer the flag pole it would I fancy look a little better.  Your artist will, I am sure, kindly look to this also: -'
[design from an album] The full title is 'Sharpe's London Magazine of Entertainment and Instruction for General Reading'
[design from an album] This design is for the spine of the edition of Shakespeare's 'Works' edited by Charles & Mary Cowden Clarke published by Bickers & Son.
[design] Dr Jenny Brown thinks that this design is for part of the paper cover of the book entitled 'The Busch. Bushel of Merrythoughts'.
